column6: Decent surveys; probably drop T2 of G and J's due to being too deep. KF stipe counts percent comp: 10% Nereo, 45% Pterygophora, 45% Saccharina dentigera
Poor visibility (1-3ft), surge, high density kelp. Basically a qualitative wash.

2 good surveys, despite the surge. Gastropods validated included: Calliostoma , Lirabuccinium dira, Nucella lamellosa. Algae included: E;rythrophyllum - red, consider this may be v abundant right now. Odonthalia washingtoniensis - red. crab - decorator Scyra acutifrons

KF and GW invert band transects only 1 meter wide due to visibility. Cryptopleura, 2 species? One with fringed edges (C. ruprechtiana) and another that has no fringes and not a well devloped midrib but is still veined like Cryptopleura

Boulder fields with large haulout of sea lions to the west and feeding gray whales in the channel to the south. Decent visibility and moderate surge. Pterogophera with heavy settlement of barnacles on the stipes; some black rockfish.

Site situated at south portion of cove, in front of keyhole arch. Surge channels and mix of Nereocystis and Macrocystis. Good visibility and several fishes, including striped surfperch and juvenile rockfish.

Nereocystis bed on the lee side of a small rock island; calm seas with NW swell, gray whales near shore, loads of krill. OS notes: Huge swarms of red mysids, white mysids, tiny gnat mysids, at Anderson Pt. Nearly 100% cover of reds, mostly Cryptopleura, some chorndrocanthus, Erythrophyllum others. Excellent crevice with many (~15) YOY rockfish (black spot on back), a large urchin, and rock scallops. Relatively little kelp other the Ptero at the beginning of the transect.

NE corner of island along protected landing beach, sunny and clear skies, no swell in huge Nereocystis bed, high densities of gelatinous zooplankton. OS notes: Holy kelp forest, what a mess.  Many species of kelp & browns, understory dominated by corallines, tunicates, hydroids. Saw Consantinia, no erythrophyllum. Saw 40cm lingcod, several kelp greenling. Followed around by a curious harbor seal, Lost GoPro…

Great visibility, approaching 7.1 m (23 ft). Site inside (south) of rocks and Nereocystis bed, protected from swell. Flooding current. OS notes: Dense canopy and understonry.  Few foliose reds, but lots of crusts - algal, sponge, bryozoan, etc. Tall canopy was about 60% Nereo and 40% Macro at the surface but more like 80% Macro, 20% Nereo at bottom. The dense canopy made it very difficult to swim and involved getting caught on lots of kelp while trying to swim through it. Huge Mysid swarms on edge of kelp and within kelp.. starting at about ft deep. (at least three types of mysids- red, white, and white-tiny)

Sunny, clear, and flat. Huge bed of mixed Nereocystis and Macrocystis, with Ulva and Fucus on top of top layer. Submerged rock formations, canyons, and caves. OS notes: Heavy Macro Canopy but relatively light understory.  Understory dominated by perennial reds like Constantinia. Observed a YOY rockfish (black spot on back near end of 2nd transect -caught on video). Also observed several rock scallop on the wall (approx 11cm diam).  Also giant truban snail on the macro shoots ~6 cm).  neither of these species were on the 30m, transect. Enormous numbers of Black Rockfish floating around this transect.
